observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor:

Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the preliminary activities before the actual conduct of inventory taking of all City’s PPE whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the inventory taking and complete all planned activities/procedures in the approved PIP and prepare the RPCPPE pursuant to Item 6.2.10 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Require the General Services Office (GSO) to update its property records based on the result of the physical inventory and reconcile with the accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts pursuant to Item 5.12 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

Instruct the GSO to initiate disposal procedures for the unlocated or non-existing PPEs following the procedures under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Submit specific legal basis for the grant of benefits, awards and rewards to all City officials and employees.

Submit information or records that monetary awards were granted only when the suggestion, inventions, superior accomplishments and other personal efforts result in monetary saving and the monetary awards granted did not exceed 20% of the savings generated pursuant to Item 6 of CSC MC No. 01;

Submit Agency’s Annual Work and Financial Plan and budget showing at least 5% of the HRD Funds allocated for the PRAISE is incorporated;

We recommended that:
The City Mayor and the concerned officials observe the fundamental principles governing the financial transactions and operations of any government agency under Section 4(1) of PD No. 1445 which states that no money shall be paid out of any public treasury or depository except in pursuance of an appropriation law or other specific statutory authority;
The City Treasurer, together with the City Budget Officer and City Accountant thoroughly review the amount to be presented in the Statement of Receipts and Expenditures in order to reflect the proper balances that could aid in the monitoring of available cash balance;
The City Treasurer adhere with Section 337 of RA No. 7160 in the disbursement of funds and ensure that payments are controlled as to availability of applicable fund and not as to available cash balance; and
The City officials who certified and approved the disbursements with insufficient cash shall be liable for the incurrence of cash overdraft/deficit.

We recommended that the City Accountant and the GSO:

Start the reconciliation of their records and undertake specific measures to eliminate the discrepancies between the two records;

Record properly the properties acquired with complete descriptions in the PPE ledger cards and in the property cards, respectively;

Maintain updated PPE ledgers and property cards, respectively so reconciliation of the two records could be done readily; and

Prepare adjusting entry to transfer the completed asset to the Public Infrastructures or to other appropriate asset accounts at the end of the year.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Submit specific legal basis for the grant of benefits, awards and rewards to all City officials and employees.

Adhere to the PRAISE principle that providing incentives and awards is founded on performance, innovative ideas and exemplary behavior, in case the basis of giving awards/incentives is the PRAISE policy;

Submit information or records that monetary awards were granted only when the suggestion, inventions, superior accomplishments and other personal efforts result in monetary saving and the monetary awards granted did not exceed 20% of the savings generated pursuant to Item 6 of CSC MC No. 01;

Submit Agency’s Annual Work and Financial Plan and budget showing at least 5% of the HRD Funds allocated for the PRAISE is incorporated; and

Carefully evaluate the validity of giving out incentives, especially the basis thereof and whether the City Officials and employees who were granted incentives are qualified to receive the same.

We reiterated our recommendation that the City Mayor and the City Accountant:
Enforce immediate settlement of outstanding cash advances totaling ₱13,837,662.98 pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 97-02 and 2012-004 dated February 10, 1997 and November 28, 2012, respectively;
Issue another set of demand letters to all accountable officers in active service whose cash advances remained not liquidated as of                December 31, 2021;
Ensure that no additional cash advances shall be granted to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance granted to him/her has been settled or a proper accounting thereof has been made pursuant to Section 89 of Presidential Decree No. 1445; and
Strictly impose the withholding of salary and the institution of other sanctions as provided under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular    No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997.

We recommended that the City Accountant and/or the City Treasurer:
Prioritize the reconciliation of intra agency accounts (Due from/to Other Funds) to eliminate the discrepancy by tracing and identifying the errors/omissions/mispostings in the recording of prior years’ transactions;
Effect the necessary correcting/adjusting entries to arrive at reliable balances of the two reciprocal accounts;
Conduct regular reconciliation of intra agency accounts to avoid accumulation of intra-agency reciprocal account discrepancies; and
Deposit daily SET collections to the SEF authorized depository account and settle other long outstanding intra receivable/payables transactions in case there are still undeposited SET collections recorded in the General Fund.

